            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>How this soil calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This soil calculator estimates how much topsoil, garden soil,
                compost, or raised bed mix you need for lawns, flower beds,
                vegetable gardens, and landscaping projects.
              </p>
              <p>It supports:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Rectangular or square beds</li>
                <li>Circular beds or planters</li>
                <li>
                  Border / ring areas (for trees, beds around patios, etc.)
                </li>
                <li>Multiple areas at once (Advanced mode)</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Soil volume formulas</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>General formula</strong></p>
                <p>\( \text{Volume} = \text{Area} \times \text{Depth} \)</p>
                <p><strong>Rectangle / square</strong></p>
                <p>\( \text{Area} = \text{Length} \times \text{Width} \)</p>
                <p><strong>Circle</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \( \text{Area} = \pi r^2 \), where \( r =
                  \frac{\text{Diameter}}{2} \)
                </p>
                <p><strong>Ring / border</strong></p>
                <p>\( \text{Area} = \pi (R^2 - r^2) \)</p>
                <p>
                  where \( R \) is the outer radius and \( r \) is the inner
                  radius.
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Unit conversions used</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>1 ft = 12 in</li>
                <li>1 m = 100 cm</li>
                <li>1 yd³ = 27 ft³</li>
                <li>1 m³ = 35.3147 ft³</li>
                <li>1 m³ = 1000 L</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The calculator converts all inputs to a consistent internal unit
                (feet and cubic feet), computes the volume, then converts back
                to cubic yards, cubic meters, and liters.
              </p>

              <h2>Typical soil depths</h2>
              <p>
                Use these common depth guidelines if you are not sure how deep
                your soil layer should be:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Topdressing an existing lawn:</strong> 0.5–1 inch
                  (1–2.5 cm)
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>New lawn (sod or seed):</strong> 4–6 inches (10–15 cm)
                  of quality topsoil
                </li>
                <li><strong>Flower beds:</strong> 6–8 inches (15–20 cm)</li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Vegetable beds / raised beds:</strong> 8–12 inches
                  (20–30 cm)
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Deep-rooted crops (tomatoes, shrubs):</strong> 12–18
                  inches (30–45 cm)
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Estimating soil weight</h2>
              <p>
                Soil is usually sold by volume, but delivery trucks and trailers
                have weight limits. If you know the approximate bulk density of
                your soil mix, you can estimate the total weight.
              </p>
              <p>Typical bulk densities:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Loose, dry topsoil: ~0.8–1.0 tons/yd³ (1200–1500 kg/m³)</li>
                <li>
                  Moist garden soil / compost mix: ~1.0–1.3 tons/yd³ (1500–1900
                  kg/m³)
                </li>
                <li>
                  Wet, clay-heavy soil: 1.3–1.5+ tons/yd³ (1900–2200+ kg/m³)
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The calculator multiplies the total volume by the bulk density
                you enter to estimate total weight in both US (tons, pounds) and
                metric (metric tons, kilograms) units.
              </p>

              <h2>Practical tips for ordering soil</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Add 5–10% extra</strong> to account for settling,
                  compaction, and measurement error.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Check bag size carefully:</strong> bags are often
                  labeled in liters or quarts; convert to cubic feet if needed.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Match soil type to use:</strong> topsoil for lawns,
                  rich organic mix for vegetables, and well-draining mixes for
                  raised beds and containers.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Consider mixing:</strong> many gardeners blend
                  topsoil, compost, and sand to improve structure and drainage.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </section>

            <!-- FAQ -->
            <section class="mt-8" id="faq">
              <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4">Soil calculator FAQ</h2>
              <div class="space-y-3">
                <details class="border rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    How do I calculate how many bags of soil I need?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    Use the calculator to find the total volume of soil in cubic
                    feet or liters, then divide by the volume of one bag. For
                    example, if you need 30 ft³ and each bag is 1.5 ft³, you
                    need 30 ÷ 1.5 = 20 bags. When you enter your bag size, the
                    tool shows the bag count automatically.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    Is it better to buy soil in bags or in bulk?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    For small projects like a few containers or a single raised
                    bed, bags are convenient. For larger projects (multiple
                    beds, whole lawns, or landscaping), bulk delivery by the
                    cubic yard is usually cheaper. Use the cubic yard result to
                    compare bulk prices with the equivalent number of bags.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    How accurate is this soil calculator?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    The math is exact for the dimensions you enter, but
                    real-world factors like uneven ground, soil compaction, and
                    moisture can change the actual amount needed. That’s why we
                    recommend adding 5–10% extra to your estimate.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    Can I use this for mulch, gravel, or compost?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    Yes. The volume formulas are the same for any loose
                    material. Just enter the area and depth you want to cover.
                    If you know the bulk density of your material, you can also
                    estimate total weight.
                  </p>
                </details>
              </div>
            </section>
